<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38218d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38218d">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38218d"> 218(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dravidian</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Another explanation of the outcastes&apos; low estate, and one that is more in consonance with western ideas is this: there are several racial strains in the Indian people. The chief of these are the <mark>Dravidian</mark> and the Aryan. There is also a Mongolian strain; and there are others. All these are believed to have been introduced from outside at different periods <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> A race called the Dravidian is supposed to have swarmed into India from the north-west at some remote, almost prehistoric period. At a later period &mdash; say 1000 <year>B.C.</year> &mdash; Aryan people followed them <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> some <font color="green">[outcastes]</font> are considered by certain authorities to be descendants of the aborigines. The myths of the Hindus represent the Aryans of the heroic ages as encountering, when they pushed southwards, repulsive little black creatures whom they could hardly believe to be human <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> These may have been the ancestors of the outcastes. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 20</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c08043a" href="c8all.htm#c08043a">VI.C.08:043(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
